  "prompt": "Why are games so much more expensive on console systems than they are on PC platforms such as Steam?",
  "response": "There are several reasons why console games tend to be more expensive than PC games:\n\n1. Licensing fees\n- Console manufacturers (Sony, Microsoft, Nintendo) charge game developers licensing fees to publish on their platforms\n- These fees are built into the game's price\n\n2. Different market dynamics\n- Console game market is more controlled and less competitive\n- PC platforms like Steam have more frequent sales and competition\n- PC digital platforms have lower distribution costs\n\n3. Development and manufacturing costs\n- Console games often require more specialized development\n- Physical game production and packaging add to expenses\n\n4. Closed ecosystem\n- Consoles have less price competition compared to open PC platforms\n- Fewer sellers means less pressure to reduce prices\n\n5. Platform-specific optimization\n- Console games require more specific development and testing\n- This can increase overall production costs\n\n6. Different business models\n- Console manufacturers often sell hardware at a loss, recouping costs through game sales\n- Game prices help subsidize console hardware\n\n7. Slower price depreciation\n- Console game prices tend to drop more slowly compared to PC games\n- Digital PC platforms are more dynamic in pricing\n\nThese factors contribute to the price difference between console and PC games, making console titles typically more expensive.",
